TOD report for San Fransico

Jingyi Cai

2022-09-21

TOD(transit-oriented development), means integrated urban places designed to bring people, activities, buildings, and public space together, with easy walking and cycling connection between them and near-excellent transit service to the rest of the city. Someone says taht TOD is a necessary foundation for long-term sustainability, equity, shared prosperity, and civil peace in cities. In this report, I chose San Francisco as the target city and explored whether San Franciscans are willing to pay for TOD through the relationship between rent and proximity of housing to transit. However, as the result shows, San Franciscans may not want to pay for TOD.

1.The process of data wrangling

In this process, I collect the data of San Francisco in 2009 and 2020. Most of the sources of the data comes from the ACS, and some of them comes from the website of the website of the BART.

Working with ACS Data

2009 Census Data

Lets Use get_acs()to get 2009 ACS data and rename them.

tracts09 <-  
  get_acs(geography = "tract",
          variables = c("B25026_001E","B02001_002E",
                        "B15001_050E","B15001_009E",
                        "B19013_001E", "B25058_001E",
                        "B06012_002E"), 
          year=2009, state=06,
          county=075, geometry=TRUE) %>% 
  st_transform('EPSG:2229')
# Let's "spread" the data into wide form
tracts09 <- 
  tracts09 %>%
  dplyr::select( -NAME, -moe) %>%
  spread(variable, estimate) %>%  #from long to wide data
  rename(TotalPop = B25026_001, 
         Whites = B02001_002,
         FemaleBachelors = B15001_050, 
         MaleBachelors = B15001_009,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001, 
         MedRent = B25058_001,
         TotalPoverty = B06012_002)


# Let's create new rate variables using mutate
tracts09 <- 
  tracts09 %>%
  mutate(pctWhite = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Whites / TotalPop, 0),#if()is true, turn the next one 
         pctBachelors = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, ((FemaleBachelors + MaleBachelors) / TotalPop), 0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),
         year = "2009") %>%
  dplyr::select(-Whites,-FemaleBachelors,-MaleBachelors,-TotalPoverty)

However, I find that if add the Farallon Islands into selection, where there is no public transportation, the scale of the map will become pretty small. So, in order to make the report clearer, this study was conducted in San Francisco excluding Farallon Islands.

tracts09 <- tracts09%>%
  filter(GEOID != "06075060400")

Tracts 2009 is now complete. Lets grab 2020 tracts and do the same thing.

2020 Census Data

tracts20 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", 
          variables = c("B25026_001E","B02001_002E",
                        "B15001_050E","B15001_009E",
                        "B19013_001E","B25058_001E",
                        "B06012_002E"), 
          year=2020, state=06, county=075, 
          geometry=TRUE, output="wide") %>%
  st_transform('EPSG:2229') %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B25026_001E, 
         Whites = B02001_002E,
         FemaleBachelors = B15001_050E, 
         MaleBachelors = B15001_009E,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001E, 
         MedRent = B25058_001E,
         TotalPoverty = B06012_002E) %>%
  dplyr::select(-NAME, -starts_with("B")) %>%
  mutate(pctWhite = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Whites / TotalPop,0),
         pctBachelors = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, ((FemaleBachelors + MaleBachelors) / TotalPop),0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),
         year = "2020") %>%
  dplyr::select(-Whites, -FemaleBachelors, -MaleBachelors, -TotalPoverty)
tracts20 <- tracts20%>%
  filter(GEOID != "06075060400" & GEOID != "06075980401")
#Combine the 2009 and 2020 data into the same data frame.
allTracts <- rbind(tracts09,tracts20)

Wrangling Transit Open Data

BART (Bay Area Rapid Transport) is similar to a short distance train system, and the BART lines link San Francisco to other cities and further away places. I download its geojson files of its stations from the website.

#install.packages("geojsonio")
library(geojson)
#install.packages("geojsonsf")
library(geojsonsf)

station <- geojsonsf::geojson_sf("BART_Station(1).geojson") %>% 
  st_transform('EPSG:2229')

Relating Subway Stops and Tracts

stationBuffers <- 
  rbind(
    st_buffer(filter(station, City == "San Francisco"), 2640) %>%  #feet and mile
      mutate(Legend = "Buffer") %>%
      dplyr::select(Legend),
    st_union(st_buffer(filter(station, City == "San Francisco"), 2640)) %>%  #takelines together
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(Legend = "Unioned Buffer"))

sanFrancisco <-
  filter(station, City == "San Francisco")
buffer <- filter(stationBuffers, Legend=="Unioned Buffer")

Make sure my way of selection

In this report, I choose the way of selecting centroids of the tracts because it captures a concise set of tracts without altering geometries. While well-reasoned, it is still subjective, and each choice will ultimately lead to different results. Such is the impact of scale problems in spatial analysis.

selectCentroids <-
  st_centroid(tracts09)[buffer,] %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(., dplyr::select(tracts09, GEOID), by = "GEOID") %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "Select by Centroids")

Get indicator Maps

In this progress, I can get the data of indicators of 2009 and 2020.

allTracts.group <- 
  rbind(
    st_centroid(allTracts)[buffer,] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allTracts) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "TOD"),
    st_centroid(allTracts)[buffer, op = st_disjoint] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allTracts) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "Non-TOD")) %>%
  mutate(MedRent.inf = ifelse(year == "2009", MedRent * 1.14, MedRent))

Figure out my final TOD Indicator Tables

The previous numbers are not final results, so we still need to figure out the final results.

allTracts.Summary <- 
  st_drop_geometry(allTracts.group) %>%
  group_by(year, TOD) %>%
  summarize(Rent = mean(MedRent, na.rm = T),
            Population = mean(TotalPop, na.rm = T),
            Percent_White = mean(pctWhite, na.rm = T),
            Percent_Bach = mean(pctBachelors, na.rm = T),
            Percent_Poverty = mean(pctPoverty, na.rm = T))

The comparion of rent between TOD and non-TOD

The first variable I select is the rent, which is one of the most obvious indicators expressing peoples willingness to pay for TOD. In 2009, rents in TOD areas were not higher than in non-TOD areas, and in 2020 rents in TOD areas are even lower than in non-TOD areas.

3.Grouped bar plot making these same comparisons.

For this study, I compared four selected Census variables across time and space.We can know more directly the difference in values between TOD and non-TOD areas.

In general, rents in TOD areas will be much lower than in non-TOD areas in both 2009 and 2020, which means that housing in TOD areas is not so attractive.The percentage of poverty in TOD is much higher than the non-TOD, and it proves the same thing. Although in 2020 the percentage of bachelor is a little bit higher in TOD, it means nothing, and there are less people in TOD than the non-TOD. So, from this step, we can not make the conclusion that San Franciscans are willing to pay for TOD. Conversely, it may means that the TOD has some negative effects on their selection.

5. The relation between rent and the distance station

#make buffers of the stations
stationBuffers <- 
  rbind(
    st_buffer(sanFrancisco, 2640) %>%
      mutate(Legend = "Buffer") %>%
      dplyr::select(Legend, Name))
#intersect the buffer of the station with tracts
tractClipped20 <- 
  st_intersection(stationBuffers, tracts20) %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop,MedRent,Name) %>%
  mutate(year = 2020) 

tractClipped09 <- 
  st_intersection(stationBuffers, tracts09) %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop,MedRent,Name) %>%
  mutate(year = 2009)            
tractGrouped09 <- tractClipped09 %>%
  group_by(Name,year) %>%
  summarize("Average Median Rent" = mean(MedRent),
            "TotalPop" = sum(TotalPop))
tractGrouped20 <- tractClipped20 %>%
  group_by(Name, year) %>%
  summarize("Average Median Rent" = mean(MedRent),
            "TotalPop" = sum(TotalPop))
intersection_0920 <- rbind(tractGrouped09,tractGrouped20)
centers = st_centroid(intersection_0920)
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = tracts09, fill = "white") + 
  geom_sf(data = tracts20, fill = "white") + 
  geom_sf(data = centers, aes(size = TotalPop,fill = TotalPop,alpha = 1),shape = 21, 
          show.legend = "point") + 
  labs(title = "Population", subtitle = "San Francisco, CA") +
  guides(alpha = FALSE)+
  guides(size = FALSE)+
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  facet_wrap(~year)+
  
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(0.1, 15))

I also graduated symbol maps of population and rent within 0.5 mile of each transit station. As the graph shows, the number of person-years even declined at some sites from 2009 to 2020. It is possible that something happened during this period to make them move away from here. But for a few sites near the northeast, the numbers rose slightly.

6.A plot of the relationship between the distance to subway stations and rent.

In this part, I create a geom_line plot that shows mean rent as a function of distance to subway stations.

allTracts <- rbind(tracts20,tracts09)

allTracts.rings <-
  st_join(st_centroid(dplyr::select(allTracts, GEOID, year)), 
          multipleRingBuffer(st_union(sanFrancisco), 47520, 2640)) %>% #union as a poly
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(allTracts, GEOID, MedRent, year), 
            by=c("GEOID"="GEOID", "year"="year")) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(distance = distance / 5280) #convert to miles
year_distance <- allTracts.rings %>%
  filter(MedRent!="NA")

year_distance <- year_distance%>%
  group_by(year,distance) %>%
  summarize("Average_rent" = mean(MedRent))

year_distance <-year_distance%>%rename(Miles = distance)
# Basic line plot with points
ggplot(data=year_distance, aes(x=Miles, y=Average_rent, group=year)) +
  geom_line(aes(color=year))+
  labs(title = "Rent as a function of distance to subway stations")+
  geom_point(aes(color=year))

Overall, rents in San Francisco rose from 2009 to 2020. But rents are lower in the mile around a subway station compared to other places. For San Francisco, the distance to the subway station may not be an important factor in their rents.

7.Conclusion: Are San Franciscans willing to pay for TOD?

Are San Franciscans willing to pay a premium to live in transit-rich areas? I hate to tell you this, but not enough has been done to fully answer this question. From the indicators selected, it seems that TOD is instead counterproductive to rents, and people are not willing to pay for TOD. But we missed some important factors. First is the scale of San Francisco, which is not very big and people may not need transit to get to their destinations. The second is that locals have a habit of driving, and most people probably prefer to drive to their destinations. Lastly is the issue of residential area preference, there are local parks and coastal areas, and probably for TOD, these landscapes are more attractive to them ```
